{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17566790","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17566790"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T23:48:47+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T23:48:47+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18881"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18881","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18881"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.7,0.12,0.08,0.07,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11614"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"81851"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11614","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11614"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18881"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67128"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"833"},{"type":"tags","id":"1309"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4974"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11633"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"27329"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27331"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27332"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27333"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27334"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27335"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43708"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"81851","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/81851"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 37-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with sudden onset of pain in the back of her right ankle. The pain occurred while jumping during a volleyball game. She heard a \u0027pop\u0027 sound and was unable to continue playing due to the pain. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears in mild discomfort. Her pulse rate is 80/min, blood pressure 125/75 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. She has an antalgic gait. There is no skin breach or obvious deformity. With her knees in prone position, the right ankle rests in a dorsiflexed position compared to the left. There is tenderness over the posterior ankle. Plantar flexion is weak and painful.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following examination findings would be most suggestive of a complete Achilles tendon rupture?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Positive Thompson test","Palpable defect in tendon","Increased passive dorsiflexion","Weakness of plantar flexion","Point tenderness over Achilles"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIn suspected Achilles tendon rupture, the \u003Cstrong\u003Epositive Thompson test\u003C/strong\u003E is the most reliable clinical finding. When performing this test, the patient lies prone with feet hanging over the edge of the bed. Squeezing the calf muscles normally causes plantar flexion of the foot; absence of this movement indicates complete rupture of the Achilles tendon.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Epalpable defect in tendon\u003C/strong\u003E may be present but can be difficult to appreciate due to local swelling and haematoma formation in the acute phase. Additionally, a palpable defect may be felt if there is a tear in the posterior aspect of the achilles and therefore may be present even if there is not a complete rupture. Whilst it forms part of Simmonds\u0027 triad, it is a less reliable diagnostic finding than Thompsons\u0027 test.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased passive dorsiflexion\u003C/strong\u003E occurs due to loss of the normal restraining effect of the Achilles tendon. While this is a useful sign, it is less specific than the Thompson test and requires comparison with the unaffected side.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWeakness of plantar flexion\u003C/strong\u003E is present in Achilles rupture but can also occur in other conditions such as posterior tibial tendon dysfunction or ankle sprains. While the gastrocnemius and soleus muscles, acting through the Achilles tendon, are the primary plantar flexors of the ankle, several other muscles can contribute to this movement even when the Achilles tendon is ruptured. These secondary plantar flexors include the flexor hallucis longus, flexor digitorum longus, tibialis posterior, peroneus longus, and peroneus brevis. Although their main functions involve toe flexion, foot inversion, or eversion, these muscles can produce some degree of plantar flexion. This explains why patients with a complete Achilles tendon rupture may still demonstrate weak plantar flexion. However, this weakness is not specific to complete achilles rupture.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPoint tenderness\u003C/strong\u003E over the Achilles tendon is a non-specific finding that occurs in both complete rupture and other conditions such as tendinopathy or partial tears.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe Thompson test has high sensitivity and specificity for complete Achilles tendon rupture, making it the most valuable clinical test for diagnosis. Other examination findings should be considered supportive evidence rather than diagnostic in isolation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Thompson test (lack of plantar flexion on calf squeeze) is diagnostic of Achilles tendon rupture","A positive Thompson test, weakness in plantar flexion, and increased ankle dorsiflexion are the key clinical findings in Achilles tendon rupture","The mechanism of sudden forced plantar flexion with an audible \u0027pop\u0027 is characteristic of Achilles tendon rupture"],"references":["Leppilahti J, Orava S. Total Achilles tendon rupture. A review. Sports Med 1998; 25:79. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/9519398/","van der Vlist AC, Breda SJ, Oei EHG, et al. Clinical risk factors for Achilles tendinopathy: a systematic review. Br J Sports Med 2019; 53:1352. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/30718234/","Aldridge T. Diagnosing heel pain in adults. Am Fam Physician 2004; 70:332. Available at: https://www.aafp.org/pubs/afp/issues/2004/0715/p332.html"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67128"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18881"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67128","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/67128"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-27T09:29:04+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-27T09:31:00+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11614"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"81851"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"34","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/34"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddb4","name":"Orthopaedics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/